  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1519327401" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1519327401" />
    <a title="Tsung" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4992851-tsung"><img alt="Tsung" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1298808605p2/4992851.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1519327401?book_show_action=true">Apr 16, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tsung" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tsung" href="/user/show/4992851-tsung">Tsung</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1519327401" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7250608926640758765">The Human Stain is a schizophrenic, if not unevenly written novel. It is as though it is written by different people, with variable success. While there is a central narrator, Nathan Zuckerman, through whose eyes and ears, we learn about the anti-hero Coleman Silk, there are different voices that make up the whole story. The most annoying one is the ranter, who keeps going on and on about Bill Clinton and his sexual indiscretions. The tirades are tiresome and irrelevant to the plot. The other vo</span>
  <span id="freeText7250608926640758765" style="display:none">The Human Stain is a schizophrenic, if not unevenly written novel. It is as though it is written by different people, with variable success. While there is a central narrator, Nathan Zuckerman, through whose eyes and ears, we learn about the anti-hero Coleman Silk, there are different voices that make up the whole story. The most annoying one is the ranter, who keeps going on and on about Bill Clinton and his sexual indiscretions. The tirades are tiresome and irrelevant to the plot. The other voice I could not appreciate was the Vietnam veteran. While PTSD is real issue among veterans, the parts showcasing Les Farley, were less than convincing. There was a philosophical voice that went on about a wide range of topics, but was more discursive than focused. Perhaps the most interesting parts of the novel involved Coleman himself. I could not help but compare him with John William’s Stoner. Both became academics from rather disparate backgrounds. Both betrayed their parents and in doing so, their origins. Both had successful but tumultuous careers. Both had affairs which earned public disdain. But Stoner has my vote over Coleman Silk.<br /><br />SPOILERS AHEAD. But I don’t think it matters much as it is revealed early in the story.<br /><br /><br /> The story is based on an actual event by one of Roth’s friends, an academic whose comment about two absent students is misconstrued as racist. His friend was not of African American descent, unlike Coleman Silk in the story. This embellishment is too clever for its own good. Coleman Silk’s act of passing (to pretend to be of a different race) was not unheard of and certainly not unique. But this plot twist did not quite realize its full potential in terms of plot development.<br /><br />The story is a bit too rambling for my liking, but there are two things which standout.<br /><br />Each successive generation of students is increasingly solipsistic. That is what probably got Coleman into trouble in the first place. The students were just ill-disciplined. It was never about racism. The addition of Coleman’s secret just adds confusion.<br /><br /><i>Today the student asserts his incapacity as a privilege. I can’t learn it so there is something wrong with it. And there is something especially wrong with the bad teacher who wants to teach it. There are no more criteria, Mr Zuckerman, only opinions.</i><br /><br />The second is the title itself. What is the human stain? In the story, it was a crow that was raised by humans and because of that, it could not mingle with or behave like the other crows and it became an outcast.<br /><br /><i>“Yeah. I suppose that’s the tragedy of human beings raising crows,” the girl replied, not exactly getting Faunia’s drift though not entirely missing it either. “They don’t recognize their own species. He doesn’t. And he should. It’s called imprinting,” the girl told her. “Prince is really a crow that doesn’t know how to be a crow.”</i><br /><br /><i>“That’s what comes of hanging around all his life with people like us. The human stain,: she said... we leave a stain, we leave a trail, we leave our imprint. Impurity, cruelty, abuse, error, excrement, semen-there’s no other way to be here. Nothing to do with disobedience. Nothing to do with grace or salvation or redemption. It’s in everyone. Indwelling. Inherent. Defining.</i><br /><br />There seems to be a vague reference to the concept of original sin in theology. The narrator seems to be against it. So what is the human stain? Was it Coleman’s racial origins that made him different? Was it Coleman’s trying to pass himself off as white that made him an outcast?<br /><br />The mix of characters was interesting. Coleman was portrayed as non-conformist, a rebel, and ultimately a martyr. But he was not a particularly endearing character so I felt no resonance or sympathy for him. Nathan Zuckerman was much more likeable, but alas, he was just a bystander. Faunia came across as cold and callous, but mitigated by her traumatic past. Delphine was spiteful. Les was just messed up.<br /><br />Conclusion: Intellectual but uninspiring read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7250608926640758765" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


